West 22nd Street | Tenth Avenue 29/04/2015 16h21 Spring in Chelsea, Manhattan. Chelsea Chelsea is a neighborhood on the West Side of the borough of Manhattan in New York City. The district's boundaries are roughly 14th Street to the south, 30th Street to the north, the western boundary of the Ladies' Mile Historic District – which lies between the Avenue of the Americas (Sixth Avenue) and Seventh Avenue – to the east, and the Hudson River and West Street to the west. To the north of Chelsea is the neighborhood of Hell's Kitchen (also known as "Clinton"), as well as the Hudson Yards; to the northeast is the Garment District; to the east are NoMad and the Flatiron District; to the southwest is the Meatpacking District; and to the southeast is Greenwich Village and the West Village. Chelsea is divided between Manhattan Community Board 4 and Manhattan Community Board 5. It contains the Chelsea Historic District and its extension, which were designated by the New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission in 1970 and 1981, respectively, and added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1977, expanded in 1982 to include contiguous blocks containing particularly significant examples of period architecture. The neighborhood is primarily residential, with a mix of tenements, apartment blocks, city housing projects, townhouses, and renovated rowhouses, but its many retail businesses reflect the ethnic and social diversity of the population. The area has a large gay population. Chelsea is also known as the center of the New York art world, with over 200 galleries in the neighborhood. Chelsea takes its name from the estate and Georgian-style house of retired British Major Thomas Clarke, who obtained the property when he bought the farm of Jacob Somerindyck on August 16, 1750. The land was bounded by what would become 21st and 24th Streets, from the Hudson River to Eighth Avenue. Clarke chose the name "Chelsea" after the manor of Chelsea, London, home to Sir Thomas More. [ Source and much more Information: Wikipedia - Chelsea ]

description._content: West Central Park | Naturalists Gate 29/04/2015 10h20 We entered the Central Park at the Naturalists Gate, a gate dedicated to the thousands who have entered Central Park to study nature under the sponsorship of the American Museum of Natural History. Left to this gate, the statue of Alexander von Humboldt. Alexander von Humboldt was a Prussian geographer, naturalist, and explorer, and the younger brother of the Prussian minister, philosopher and linguist Wilhelm von Humboldt (1767–1835). Humboldt's quantitative work on botanical geography laid the foundation for the field of biogeography. Humboldt's advocacy of long-term systematic geophysical measurement laid the foundation for modern geomagnetic and meteorological monitoring. More information about Alexander von Humboldt: Wikipedia Upper West Side The Upper West Side is a neighborhood in the borough of Manhattan, New York City, that lies between Central Park and the Hudson River and between West 59th Street and West 110th Street. The Upper West Side is sometimes also considered by the real estate industry to include the neighborhood of Morningside Heights. Like the Upper East Side, the Upper West Side is an affluent, primarily residential area with many of its residents working in more commercial areas in Midtown and Lower Manhattan. It has the reputation of being home to New York City's cultural, intellectual hub (with Columbia University located at the north end of the neighborhood), and artistic workers (with Lincoln Center located at the south end), while the Upper East Side is traditionally perceived to be home to commercial and business types. The neighborhood is also abbreviated "UWS". [ Source & more: Wikipedia - Upper West Side NYC ]

Taking a break from packing my personal items, a work vacation in Brooklyn doing a 12-on, 12-off schedule of packing, trashing, and recycling.  I might as well start taking pics of the apartment that's already been part of part of my life for 30 years and will continue to be so only for the next 2 weeks.

This Old Law Tenement with its distinctive dumbell-style layout is definitely from the late 19th century.  Judging by the size of the interior courtyard the building was probably built or modified in accordance with the Tenement House Act of 1879 but not in compliance with the New Law designs stipulated by a superseding act passed during 1901.  Although the front seems more modern the real bricks, the varicolored brick patterns, and Beaux Arts style etched sandstone that can also be found on some old public schools suggests otherwise, late Old Law perhaps.  Regardless, it's home.

The light switch in the living room glows a steady orange when it's in the off position, a warm glow that reminded me of Michael Whelan's “Nightmare in Red” that was used for Sepultura's “Beneath the Remains” album art.  With the tripod up and the lights out I can't use the flip screen.  Obviously it will affect the scene's lighting but just as important is that I would be totally blind.  Half blind is better than total blindness so I use an eye solely for the electronic view finder, wedging the intervalometer's control cable on the tripod only when the camera took the first shot and it slowly performed dark frame subtraction with the shutter closed. 

The room is now a depthless black save for some bluish shaft of light that managed to creep past the curling vinyl shade and blood-red window cloth.  Suddenly a thump is heard, then another.  The silence followed is brief as tiny creaking began to find their way through the vinyl tiles, betraying the presence of pre-war floorboards beneath them that were held on top of old warped joists with rusted nails.

Silence.  The bluish fog from the lit viewfinder was hanging in front of my left eye like a distracting stain as I search the room using my right eye in vain.  The creaking begins again, but this time it was joined by the serpentine rustling of plastic bags and debris, crawling closer.  It stop again, but again only momentarily.  The dark grabbed my leg.

“Whrew?”

The dark was also Oreo's element and it was obvious from the jumping over boxes and the crinkling of plastic bags from her waving tail that she was excited to welcome me into it.  She drop her paw from my leg and brush against it as the final exposures were done.

Flipping the view screen out cast jagged shadows throughout the room while bathing the rest of it in an unnatural cold tone.  I look down and gave a smile.  Oreo is down near my feet, standing on her front legs but resting on her hind.  As I started to review my images Oreo's cheerful tail abruptly became still.  I gave her a quick glance and I notice that she's not looking at me anymore.  Instead she's staring intently, at something.  I quickly reach for the light...

“My black cat Magic
Mesmerized by something in the hallway
Who's to say what's living in the Darkness?
Who is to say if a black cat can sense it?”
-King Diamond, Black of Night
